quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to set a cookie named 'logged' with the value 1 and an expiration time of 1 hour.
[!raw!]
setcookie({0}, {1}, {2});

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Cookies[/h1]

The following example creates a cookie named "user" with the value "John". The cookie will expire after 30 days, which is written as 86,400 * 30, in which 86,400 seconds = one day. The '/' means that the cookie is available throughout the entire website.

We then retrieve the value of the cookie "user" (using the global variable [b]$_COOKIE[/b]). We also use the [b]isset()[/b] function to find out if the cookie is set: [code format="php"]<?php
$value = "John";
[b]setcookie[/b]("user", $value, time() + (86400 * 30), '/'); 

if(isset($_COOKIE['user'])) {
  echo "Value is: ". $_COOKIE['user'];
}
//Outputs "Value is: John"
?>[/code]
[note]The [b]setcookie()[/b] function must appear BEFORE the <html> tag.
The value of the cookie is automatically encoded when the cookie is sent, and is automatically decoded when it's received. Nevertheless, [b]NEVER[/b] store sensitive information in cookies.[/note]
